        <body>

            <pb n="1"/>
            <p><hi rend="underline">Confidential</hi></p>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>New York</placeName>
                <date>February 8<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 5614.</date></p>
            <p>Rev<hi rend="sup">d</hi>
                <persName>Isaac Leeser</persName></p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Esteemed Friend</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Enclosed in an &#8220;effusion&#8221; of<lb/> a &#8220;theme&#8221; <sic>sensatively</sic> affecting the
                &#8220;environs&#8221; of my heart&#59; which<lb/> I send to you by the &#8220;south west passage&#8221; to
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName><lb/> for publication&#44; provided you deem it
                fit to grace the pages<lb/> of The Occident. If you conclude to present it I
                should<lb/> feel obliged by your correcting any errors either in <sic>grammer</sic>
                or<lb/> punctuation which your practiced eye will readily discov<add>er</add></p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Should you differ with my views&#44; and think it necessary<lb/> to oppose them I beg you
                will do so&#44; in such a strain as<lb/> will not give my adversaries any cause for
                exultation.<lb/> If you think the opinions expressed by me&#44; would afford<lb/> my
                enemies a good weapon to lay hold of&#44; especially<lb/> at the present time&#44; you will
                please return the M. S.<lb/> to me&#58; but as I consider &#8220;Prayer the railroad&#8221; to
                Heaven<lb/> and wishing to keep the &#8220;Car upon the track&#8221; I have in my<lb/>
                &#8220;coruscant effusion&#8221; gently alluded to the reckless speed of<lb/> our Modern prayer
                sayers and at the same time paid<lb/> a high and deserved compliment to those &#8220;pious
                men<lb/> of ancient days.&#8221; I trust you will not consider<lb/> my &#8220;Rail Road&#8221;
                Metaphor an infringement upon the<lb/> patent of the &#8220;North West line&#8221; or that I
                desire to<lb/> start an opposition to that road heavenward&#58; yet<lb/> I am candid
                enough to admit I believe my road<lb/> if properly constructed would offer as good
                accomo&#8211;<lb/>&#8211;dations to the bestowed of charity as the North West./</p>

        </body>
